\maketitle

\section{}

\subsection*{January 4, 2012}

I am travelling to Boston today to attend a math conference and to present a 30
minute talk on my work on the left nullstellensatz.

I am not excited about having to do this.  (1) I dread math conferences. (2) It
is lonely being away from my family; I have come to depend on them, and I love
them dearly. (3) Travel is hard, especially since I have been under the weather
the past couple of days; I am now sure that I have a sinus infection.

My dread in having to make this trip has really shifted my focus onto my family.

Before this vacation, I had been wondering about what could have been if my
talents in math had been better utilized.  As I saw it, I was born with great
gifts, yet I had been placed (or later on placed myself) in average/below
average educational environments.  I thought that if I had just had the right
advising, or if I hadn't had had certain negative influences in my childhood, I
could have done a lot more.  Going into this vacation, I was sorry that instead
of reaching for greatness and glory in the mathematics world I was reaching for
an easy yet unremarkable life as an actuary.

Over this vacation, especially early on, I have worked on math in intense
spurts.  The benefit of this was that I was able to prove the left
nullstellensatz; in my own small world view, this is a great result.  This
shifted how I view my time as a PhD student.

Up to that, I had solved one problem which took me approximately a month to
solve during my second year.  This result was good enough for a dissertation.  I
wasted a lot of time simply revising my work.  In addition I had solved a couple
of minor things which I was not going to publish and I had worked on the left
nullstellensatz paper.  As it was, the left nullstellensatz paper was to be
published even without my latest result.  Basically, I had scratched the surface
of the left nullstellensatz, and that was to be a paper.  Other than that, I saw
that I had a lot of time where I wasn't thinking about research.  Over the past
year, I had basically given up on research all together.  I viewed even my time
as a PhD student as me not truly maximizing my potential, and as such, I didn't
have great results to show for it.

During the time when I was originally working on the left nullstellensatz paper,
I viewed that problem as ``the big one''.  I felt that if I could just solve the
left nullstellensatz that I would somehow be validated.  In hindsight, I
probably had a false view of the importance of the problem, but it is still a
good result.  Still in my view, the left nullstellensatz is a much more
impressive result than what I previously have proven.   Therefore, in my inner
narrative, after having not done research for about a year, I took a week to
solve the biggest math problem of my life.

This experience really gave me a taste of life doing serious mathematical
research.  I got to experience what it was like to achieve solving a significant
(at least in my head) problem.  For that I felt like my talent was validated.  I
am smart enough to do math research.  On the other hand, I didn't feel
fulfilled.  My family is more important to me than wordly success.  As I worked
on my math problem, I took myself away from my family mentally.  No success
outside the home can make up for failure in the family.

\subsection*{January 6, 2012}

I spent the afternoon with my old mission companion, Elder Viriato.  I got to
spend time with his whole family, including 3 kids and his wife.  We went to a
Brazilian restaurant in my beloved Framingham, which was good.  I am glad to be
able to be friends with an old mission companion.

Also, I blew off the afternoon session of the conference.

I had more thoughts about my future career path.

To my surprise, I enjoyed the math conference.  I had results to share; I didn't
have to rely on my lame work on harmonic polynomials; it made me feel like I
belonged there; also, I enjoyed working out my results with my advisor's
collaborators; through explaining my results, I was stretched and even thought
of new angles for making my results even more polished.  It was a better taste
of how being a professor is.

This gave me some pause to think of whether I am making the correct choice to
pursue a career outside of academia.  I will say that I have not gone about
mathematical research in the right way.  First, I didn't read mathematical
papers, nor did I care much about them.  Second, I didn't seek out open problems
for me to work on; I could have been the master of the situation and picked
things that I wanted to do; in doing this, I would have needed to read up on the
field I was studying, going over papers to see what had been done and, if
necessary, how it had been done.  Third, I could have time blocked more
effectively.  As I see it, a big stumbling block was that I didn't give myself
enough help or outside ideas so that I was just figuring out everything for
myself.

Included in the things to do differently is talking to people.  I dislike
talking to people much more than I do reading mathematical papers.  I just
realize that it is important.

Therefore, through this conference I have caught a vision of what a career in
mathematical research could be, and I felt the excitement of making new
mathematical discoveries.  In a way it will be sad to give it up.

Why must I give it up.  I haven't forgotten all of the nights that I have been
in agony thinking about some math problem.  I haven't forgotten about all of the
lousy tasks that go with the joy of mathematical discovery.  I prefer to make
more money.  I prefer to work less hours so that I have more time with my
family.



\section{}

\subsection*{February 9, 2012}

Today Allison and I completed a digital fast.  We decided for a whole day that
we would avoid our usual round of Internet and television consumption.  I found
the day to be invigorating.  I have been, for a while now, wanting to do
something about my out of control digital consumption, but I haven't been able
to commit myself to anything.  I hope that as a result of today that I will be
even more motivated to curb my digital diet.

\section{}

\subsection*{March 30, 2012}

For the past almost two weeks we have been in Utah seeing both of our families.
I appreciated the time I was able to spend with my mom and brother Craig, and
now we are on the second stint in St. George at Allison's family's home.  I love
how much everyone loves lil' Anna.  I am really enjoying raising Anna.

I have spent the past while in a stupor over gadgets.  Here is my story.

Over a month ago Allison and I performed a ``digital fast''.  We took the day to
essentially not comsume digital media.  I, in particular, was sick of being
addicted to digital media.  I loved it and wanted to cut back the next day too.
However things have devolved since then.

The first interesting event was that when Allison went to bed after our digital
fast, I decided to get things done.  In the midst of this, I carelessly broke my
laptop screen.  In light of the day's events, my reaction was to immediately
regret purchasing the laptop.  It turned out that I was able to buy a screen
replacement (for about \$100) and my brother Craig kindly did the work of
replacing the screen last week.  In the meantime, I brought out my old laptop --
nicknamed ``The Beast'', it has a broken hinge and can only be used if the
screen
is propped up against a wall -- and used it to complete my school work.  This
made me further regret my laptop purchase because the Beast worked for what I
needed, and further, I enjoyed using its larger keyboard to type out my
assignments.  I also note that if I were to take the SSD from my newer laptop
and put it in the Beast, the Beast would be even better.

The second thing that happened was that I got around to selling some stuff on
Craigslist.  I remembered that it is possible to sell things on eBay and
Craigslist and get money.  For example, I recently sold my convertible
netbook/tablet for almost what my mom paid for it.

The third thing is that I became aware that I am eligible for a phone upgrade.

The final thing that really tipped me over the edge was my tablet.  A few
different things happened with my tablet.

First, after about a week of owning my tablet, I installed an update from
Samsung to the tablet which made it, in my opinion, uglier and worse.  I tried
out a bunch of different custom roms to make the tablet better, but the only
ones that I really liked were the ones that were based on the newest version of
the Android operating system.  This came with some drawbacks: the camera doesn't
work; depending on the rom, the operating system can be unstable; there are apps
which simply don't work on the tablet; I haven't been able to change the font to
a font I like; I haven't been able to connect my tablet directly to my laptop.

Second, I sometimes pop by the UCSD bookstore to look at the Apple electronics.
I began to notice how the iPad did some things a lot better than my tablet.  The
web browsing exerience was night and day.  Apps are made for the iPad, whereas
on Android they are just stretched out phone apps; also, there are simply a lot
more apps -- like note taking apps or video apps -- which Android doesn't have.
The iPad has a beautiful Helvetica aethsetic.  This comparison was further
brought to light when I brought my tablet to my mom's and saw firsthand all of
these great points.

Third, I became somewhat addicted to certain games on my tablet.  Of course
these games are better on the tablet than on the phone.

Adding all this together, what happened is that in my mind I had a giant choice
presented to me as to whether or not I should sell all my gadgets and get new
ones or not.  More specifically, a line of reasoning presented itself.  I can
now see that the iPad is a better tablet than any Android tablet on the market.
Also, the iPad just had a refresh, which is the best time to buy an Apple device
(I can get the newest one at the normal price, or I can get the old one for less
than ever).  However, the biggest thing which would hinder my owning an iPad is
that one needs the iTunes music player in order to successfully set up an
``iDevice''.  For most people this is not a problem, however i use Linux, which
doen't have iTunes, and I do not want to use Windows.  Well, I have had
thoughts about selling my laptop anyway.  It then becomes feasible to buy a
Macbook.  In fact, there is a not so bad deal on a refurbished Macbook Air that
I would enjoy having.  Doing this wouldn't be too bad because (a) I can dual
boot to Linux and (b) I like certain parts of OS X, including the multitouch
gestures, stability of the operating system, and the increased availability of
apps.  So now, if I am on this route and I now own an Apple computer, there is
one phone which works best with Apple computers: the iPhone.  Certainly there
are things that I like about the iPhone: it is attractive, the metal casing
makes it feel premium compared to plastic Android phones, and it has the same
pleasing qualities the iPad has.  Sure, Android is cheaper, syncs better to
Google apps, which I use extensively, and lacks a built in GPS, lacks 4G, but
the one more thinks about it, the more one sees that one could get buy just fine
with one.  And then, while I am at it, Apple TV is only \$99 and allows any of
these Apple devices to stream to it wirelessly.

This is why Apple is the largest company right now.  Basically, with their
consumer lock-in strategy, I went from considering trading one of my gadgets to
get one of theirs to trading my three biggest gadgets to get three of theirs.
The total cost of this?  Estimating things out, I might spend \$1000 or more to
do this replacement.  That's crazy!  True, Apple products depreciate at a lower
rate than competing electronics, but \$1000 is a lot to spend considering I was
considering a low cost option of trading a tablet for a similarly-priced tablet.
 Especially crazy is that this started out with me doing a digital fast and
actually enjoying it.  Making this even more crazy is my preference for free and
open computing; I like not being tied down to one company (Apple), compelled by
my past spending to rely on their products and services; I like Linux.

This has led me to conclude that I need to get rid of my tablet.  I know this
will be disappointing to my wife, however there are two big reasons for this:
(1) the tablet only increases my time wasting and really I don't do anything
productive with it; (2) I went from being more than satisfied with my gadgets
when I had a laptop and a phone to being totally dissatisfied with all of my
gadgets -- the laptop and phone are the same, and I only added to what I have.

As a footnote, I probably will get a new phone, and it's going to be Android.

\section{}

\subsection*{April 20, 2012}

\subsubsection*{Events}

My mom and Paul are in town to visit because it is Spring break for the kids.
So far we have gone out to eat some, Allison made a Sunday dinner, and my mom
has enjoyed taking care of Anna for us.

\subsubsection*{Problem}

I have had a rough time the past while.
I feel the way I feel after I have fasted and have needed to make a big change.

On a low level, I felt like it might be all related to the issue of which
phone I should get.  I felt like I should get an Android phone.  I got an
Android phone, one of the best ones on the market.  I still feel lousy.
So it could be something larger.  Or it could be that secretly I still wanted
to justify getting an iPhone instead. (The iPhone is ``more beautiful'', it has
the best selection of apps, and Apple keeps it up to date---i.e., it is cutting
edge all of the time without having to be tinkered with---and it has the best
camera; however, it doesn't have 4G, I'm more afraid of them breaking, and I am
invested in Google's cloud---which, by the way, is better than Apple's cloud.)

On a higher level, I felt like it could be my gadget addiction.  I have tried
harder to not idle around with my gadgets.  Still I feel lousy.


My next idea is that the thing I can do is to live better in every way I can:
go to bed and wake up early; eat healthily and regularly; exercise vigorously;
do better scripture studies; etc.

\subsubsection*{Night Thoughts}

Here is a list (for my own sake) to help me remember why I want an Android
phone instead of an iPhone:

\begin{itemize}
 \item Free turn-by-turn navigation.
 \item Gmail is better on Android (and I like Gmail).
 \item You can look at the file system.
 \item You don't have to use iTunes.
 \item More resistant towards drops.
\end{itemize}

\subsection*{April 12, 2012}

I have had a rough while being distraught over my gadgets.
Today I decided to take back the Galaxy Nexus.
I decided to get instead the iPhone 4S.
I immediately knew that I needed to sell it.
Allison was also not pleased with my choice.
In hindsight, this might work out fine because I am pleased with my current
phone, so by selling the iPhone, I can make a profit, thereby capitalizing on
the subsidy which Verizon offers on the iPhone.

\subsubsection*{iPhone Experience}

I was mostly underwhelmed with the iPhone experience as I played with it
tonight.  Here is what stood out to me, both pro and con:


\begin{itemize}
 \item Google apps are lousy on the iPhone.  On the other hand, they are the
best thing about Android.  Gmail is the best mail service (in my opinion); on
iPhone the Gmail app doesn't have all the same features. Google Voice saves me
from having a texting plan; on iPhone, I found the Google Voice app to be
lacking.  Google Maps Navigation is the best free GPS app.
\item While Mobile Safari on the iPad is, from what I've seen, far superior to
tablet Android browsing, I found that on the iPhone I didn't like Safari as
well as Android's browser.  The main thing that bugged me was that for some
reason on iPhone one cannot scroll quickly.
\item The camera on the iPhone performed well.
\item Every app in the App Store works.  On my wonky devices, the same cannot
be said.
\item The glass and metal iPhone didn't necessarily feel any nicer than the
plastic phones I have been using.
\item I wouldn't feel comfortable using an iPhone without a home computer on
which iTunes was installed.  I have no such computer available.
\item As far as everything else, the iPhone was useable.  There are nice things
about it.
\end{itemize}

Given the cons of the iPhone, and given that my old phone ``just works'' when
it comes to my core needs (Making phone calls, Gmail, Google Voice, Music,
Internet, etc.), I believe that my old phone will continue to serve me well.

\subsubsection*{Galaxy Nexus Experience}

While I am at it, here are my pros and cons of the Samsung Galaxy Nexus

\begin{itemize}
 \item Phone service would drop from time to time.  This was an epic fail from
my perspective given that the primary responsibility of a smarphone is to be a
phone.
\item Apps worked on it.
\item It was light.
\item This goes for the iPhone too, but I felt uneasy carrying around such an
expensive gadget.  I always was afraid it would break.
\item The phone was super fast.  The 4G was super fast.
\item The camera was worse than my old phone.
\end{itemize}

\subsection*{April 13, 2012}

I am probably going to sell the iPhone 4S I now own.  I went to Verizon
yesterday to reactivate my old HTC Droid Incredible.
Although I like things about the iPhone, I am underwhelmed with it, and in
contrast, I appreciate better the things my Droid does.
I think I am going to go low cost, low distraction as far as my gadgets go.  I
need to focus on other things in my life other than gadgets.

I listed it on Craigslist last night and didn't get any hits.  I will lower the
price on it.  I would settle for \$450 to \$500 for it.

\subsection*{April 15, 2012}

I am still in my phone dilemma.

It would have been easier if I didn't buy any new phone.
I would have spent no money, and I would have a simple, cheap phone which does
everything necessary for me.
I can still take back the iPhone, but then I won't be able to get a subsidized
new phone.  This might be a good option if I want to not have a smartphone once
my contract is up.

I now have the iPhone, and I basically \textit{have to} sell it.  Craigslist is
not panning out right now, and so I might have to do eBay.  I prefer not to do
eBay because (a) they take a cut of the sale and (b) I have to figure out
shipping on it.

The other option is to simply start using the iPhone.  I will say that as I
have dinked around with the iPhone as it has been sitting on my table for the
past few days, I have found the following:
\begin{itemize}
 \item I have gotten used to Mobile Safari.  I figured out the trick to type in
an address or a search.  The reading mode option is right up my alley.  I am an
irrational fan of Helvetica, which iPhone uses, and on the other hand, Android
uses Droid Sans or now Roboto as its default sans-serif font.  All mobile sites
are optimized for the iPhone, whereas on Android some fail.  I also have become
more accepting that Mobile Safari doesn't do super fast scrolling because how
can one see everything on a page if one scrolls past it super fast.

\item I inadvertently plugged the iPhone into Ubuntu and much to my surprise
the iPhone's file folder opened.  In Ubuntu, I would be able to import my
pictures with no hassle.  I did not realize this was an option.  To do music,
however, one still needs iTunes.

\item I haven't changed my opinion of Google apps on the iPhone, but I have
softened my stance about how well I would be able to integrate Google with the
iPhone.

\item I noticed the iPhone won't let me run an app with sound and play music at
the same time.
\end{itemize}
Basically, I have found more and more reasons to convince myself to just use
the iPhone.  There is, however, an irrational force compelling me to stay with
Android: peer pressure.  (Actually, whether or not it is irrational is
debatable.)  Allison, despite having said that she would let me do what I want,
clearly likes Android better, and would love me to like Android better.  All of
Allison's family uses Android as well, which makes our ties to it even
stronger.  My brother Craig uses Android, and one of the things we can actually
bond over is using Android and hating Apple.  Finally, there is just something
uncool about liking Apple.  (For a certain subset of society, the opposite is
true---Apple is cool---but for the rest of us, Android is cooler.)  One
of the main reasons is that Apple is locked down and takes advantage of
things for their profit.  (They are a business, and the purpose of a
business is to make money, but still.)  Socially, I want to be squarely in
Android camp. In practice, when it comes down to picking a device and actually
using it, I am torn. I am disappointed with Android.  The Galaxy Nexus was cool
in some ways, but in a lot of ways it bugged me; every other new phone had
bloatware, out of date operating systems, and ugly custom skins slapped all over
them; my Android tablet has been a letdown; I am very uninspired by anything
Android.

Putting aside the social reasons, it is still somewhat of a tricky decision.
The social aspect makes it impossible.  I am planning on taking my old Android
and leaving the new iPhone to Utah for sure because I can't handle anyone
knowing that I have the iPhone now.

\subsection*{April 16, 2012}

I tried to be more productive today.  I ended up doing a lot of paper writing.
I have a paper I am working on by myself.  My professor asked me a couple weeks
ago a question about matrices of non-commutative polynomials.  I somewhat
quickly found out that I could extend my Left Nullstellensatz result to
matrices of polynomials.  I have been trying to write this up.  It is not a big
priority, and perhaps I ought not spend too much time on it, however, I do want
to finish it soon because I figure I won't be writing math papers for much
longer.

I have pondered somewhat more on the social aspects of the brands I use.
Here are some thoughts:
\begin{itemize}
 \item Above all, I need to seek the Spirit in my Android vs. iPhone decision.
I will note that I may need to go back to Android, which also happens to be the
socially acceptable decision.
\item Unfortunately, I have looked down on iPhone users over the time in which
I have been an Android user.  I did it even today.  I am glad that I am now
aware of it, but I ought not judge others over their brand usage.  (A case can
be made that brand usage correlates with personality characteristics, but
that's not something I need to read into.)  
\item I also have been biased over the past two years towards Android and have
not seen the benefits of iPhone. (After playing around with the iPhone, I see
the benefits of Android more clearly as well though.)
\end{itemize}

\subsection*{April 18, 2012}

I had a dream last night in which we were going to visit a pair of converts
from my mission in Brazil (Daiane and Liliane).  I really would like to find
out what has become of them.  I am impressed with the feeling that I was
treated well on my mission by them.  I am grateful for the opportunity I had to
serve a mission and to have been called to where I was called to.  There are
negative spins I can put on things about my mission (certain lousy companions,
my lack of social skills, getting in a car accident, etc.) but I was really
blessed by it.

\subsubsection*{Poetry}

I just had a thought about my last semester of Utah State.
I had a poetry class where I wrote poetry.
I had an odd point of view at Utah State.
Is that what brought out my weird poetry?
It almost makes me want to write about it;
the only thing is I mostly don't like poetry anymore
to want to write about it.
(I don't really connect with poetry;
I just liked my weird poems.)

Here are some of my poems:

\subsubsection*{The Sixth Sense}

\noindent I love technology.

\

\noindent See all the things you can do now:

\noindent Every day you can watch Law and Order reruns for hours;

\noindent Every day you can play hearts online.

\

\noindent Daybreak. When I check my

\noindent E-mail I see that the crocodile hunter died last night;

\noindent A candle in the wind‰ÛÓI would've liked to have known you*;

\noindent Dead at age 44.

\

\noindent People see me as I

\noindent Empty out garbage

\noindent Out in the street for mechanical

\noindent Pick up; as I walk across the

\noindent Lawn, up the steps, and

\noindent Enter the house, I wipe blades of grass off my bare feet.

\subsubsection*{Commentary}

I wrote this as an acrostic because I thought that was fun.
Half of the things here were sparked by memories of the summer of 2006;
I was home recovering from my broken leg.
The other half are from when I was at school that fall.

\subsection*{The Mathematician}

\noindent I have a one-centimeter-tall gremlin inside my head;

\noindent Reminds me of problems I have to solve;

\noindent Religiously chants numbers in my ear (4, 8, 15, 16, 23, 42...)

\

\noindent As I write this poem,

\noindent I imagine some soft, pleasing background music; 5

\noindent I invite you, gentle reader, to do the same;

\noindent Music like ‰ÛÏCandle in the Wind (1997)‰Û? by Elton John;

\noindent I heard that song on the radio the other day‰ÛÓ

\noindent That's a really good song.

\

\noindent If you have to take a lower salary 10

\noindent To get a job with Internet access,

\noindent I suggest in the strongest possible terms you do it;

\

\noindent Where have you gone, O. J. Simpson?

\noindent What have you been doing?

\noindent I heard somewhere you sold your 15

\noindent Heisman trophy (1968) and took up golf;

\noindent Did you kill your wife?

\noindent Probably‰ÛÓwe all think so. \footnote[1]{O.J. confirmed our beliefs
recently with the announcement of his book \textit{If I Did
It.}}

\

\noindent I fell out of the top bunk today (7:00 am),

\noindent I tried to grab a pillow which had fallen 20

\noindent (My most comfortable pillow),

\noindent But in my dreamy state I overestimated my reach;

\noindent As I lay on the carpet looking upward,

\noindent I realized I had another pillow in my bed.

\

\noindent A random walk, 25

\noindent Sometimes called a ‰ÛÏdrunkard's walk‰Û?,

\noindent is a simple stochastic process,

\noindent Where one takes a step to the right with probability p,

\noindent Or a step to the left with probability 1 ‰öÕ p. \footnote[2]{$"$Random
Walk,$"$ Wikipedia.org, $<$http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Random\_walk$>$}


\noindent Obla-Di, Obla-Da 30

\noindent What words do I most want to repeat in my life?

\noindent Happiness, Luck, Serenity, Silliness;

\noindent Except the gremlin inside my head eats words

\noindent And spits numbers.

\subsubsection*{Commentary}

This is basically a mashup of things that happened to me (falling out of my bed
at college), pop culture that ``hit me'' the right way (``Candle in the Wind'',
  O.J. Simpson, \textit{Lost}, ``Obla-Di, Obla-Da'', and a line from the
Brazilian song ``Palavras Repetidas''), and just random things (Internet at
your job, the mathematical concept of a random walk).

\subsection*{Think Weekend at Bernie's}

\noindent I tore open a pillow from his bed

\noindent And filled his chest with the insides‰ÛÓ

\noindent Feathers, straw, wood chips‰ÛÓ

\noindent To stop up the blood.

\noindent Merlin reentered the room with a girdle

\noindent Pulled it onto Arthur‰Ûªs wide torso

\noindent Squeezed as tightly as he could

\noindent Closing the wound.

\

\noindent I complained to Merlin that this wouldn't work.

\noindent I told him that people would find out what we had done.

\noindent I told him that people would eventually find out that dragons don't
really exist.

\noindent Merlin laughed: ‰ÛÏPeople will believe whatever we tell them, my boy!‰Û?

\

\noindent As Arthur's court poet,

\noindent I recently wrote about how the king had slain a mighty dragon

\noindent Which had come to Camelot to make trouble;

\noindent Arthur ran Excalibur through the dragon's throat and lungs,

\noindent Causing the vile beast to choke on his own smoke.

\

\noindent Merlin spread some strong-smelling potion over the undershirt

\noindent To cover the smell of blood and death.

\noindent I found some ladies‰Ûª powder

\noindent Applied it to his face to make it appear artificially white.

\noindent His limp body fit into the armor fairly easily.

\noindent We topped his head with a crown

\noindent And placed that famous sword at his side;

\noindent Arthur was ready to lead us into battle.

\

\noindent We could hear the party starting,

\noindent In commemoration of Arthur slaying the dragon:

\noindent Feet stomping,

\noindent A harp and lute playing softly,

\noindent Young squires bragging,

\noindent Young maidens gossiping;

\

\noindent When we came down the stairs with Arthur,

\noindent His arms extended over our shoulders,

\noindent The party stopped, stared,

\noindent Then bowed reverently to their king,

\noindent That mighty dragon slayer.

\noindent We couldn't help but smile.

\subsection*{Commentary}

This one is the last poem I could actually find.
It is the least personal, but as such, is the most understandable by regular
people.
I didn't really have anything to say here.
I put in things that sounded important (``People will believe whatever
we tell them, my boy!'')
How would I revise this if I had to do it today?
Would I give it more meaning?
Would I give it a sharper edge?
\noindent

