iPhone?)  Or am I to conclude that through bad choices (i.e. buying the iPhone
and backing myself into a corner) I limited my options, so I now get different
spiritual promptings leading me to salvage my situation?

I don't really know right now what the answer is.

\subsection*{April 22, 2012}

I'm still having problems getting to a good place spiritually.

A huge problem for me is thoughts.  I get obsessed with unimportant (but
fun) things.  I dwell on topics for a long time.  Right now, the topic has been
the iPhone saga.  (This is not to mention that I have killed a lot of time by
playing games on my iPhone.)

The devil's advocate side of this (literally) is that my focus is also what
has allowed me to succeed in school.  I have attacked math problems with the
full force of my obsessive attention until I solved them.  I do recognize that
there is a time and a place for focusing on vocationally important problems;
however, balance is a valuable thing to have in one's life.

At church, we had a good topic for a lesson, following the promptings of the
Holy Ghost, which ties along with this.  How can I cultivate the Spirit in my
life if I am filling my thoughts with other things.  It doesn't matter that my
``other things'' are typically benign and good in moderation, in excess they
crowd out the most important things in my life.

Here is something I pulled up from scripture study about the Savior (Stephen
Robinson, \textit{Believing
Christ}, 115):

\begin{quote}
 Do not misunderstand me.  I am not suggesting here that Jesus in any way
indulged in unclean thoughts, for that would be sin, and he indulged in nothing
sinful.  I do not believe that he ‰Û÷struggled‰Ûª or ‰Û÷wrestled‰Ûª with temptations.
My only point is that he was as vulnerable to suggestions and impulses coming
into his mind from his mortal nature, a nature inherited from his mortal mother,
as any of us.  He simply paid no attention to those suggestions, and he
immediately put them out of his mind.  The ability of the flesh to suggest, to
entice, was the same for him as it is for us, but unlike the rest of us, he
never responded to it.  He didn‰Ûªt ponder, deliberate, or entertain the sinful
options even as theoretical possibilities--‰Û?he gave no heed unto them.‰Û?
\end{quote}

\subsection*{April 24, 2012}

I am having a really hard time staying on task today.
I have two conflicting desires.
The first is the pure desire to do what is right, useful, and productive.
The second is the desire to make myself feel good through entertainment,
devices, etc.
I know in my mind that I ought not give in to entertaining myself.
However, it seems hard to make the lifestyle switch to doing just that.

Yesterday I tried to keep my thoughts on important things and off of
unimportant things.  I did well at this for a while.  As the night wore on,
however, I realized that if I lived according to this one principle, I would
have to give up most of my entertainment.  As I see it, my daytime hours are
best spent on work.  My nighttime hours are best spent on family.  This leaves
no time for alone time.

Another way of looking at this is that I am addicted to procrastinating,
entertainment, technology, etc.  Time spent feeding that addiction is bad for
me right now.  Yet, because I am addicted, I don't know how to stop.

