\subsection*{May 1, 2012}

I am going to have to break it to my brother Craig that I now have an iPhone.
I think he is going to be upset about it because he is hardcore anti-Apple.
I am trying to think of what to say to him:

\subsubsection*{Problems with Android}

The biggest problem with Android for me is lack of support.
I'll break it down into a few cases.

\subsubsection*{Most Android Phones}

The large majority of Android phones don't get regular updates.
I would be especially skeptical of owning one that was a year old or older
because I don't think it would get more updates.
Also they have skins over the software which I hate.
They are ugly and make the phone slower.

\subsubsection*{Nexus Phones}

In theory the solution to this problem is the Nexus line.
I bought a Nexus phone.
It had bad reception; the Internet thought this was a software problem, but
Verizon wasn't authorizing updates to it yet.  It also had relatively bad
battery life (because it was 4G) and a subpar camera.
Also, instead of just being able to open it like a USB device
(which was nice for me)
it had a funky protocol which made file transfers slower; also, it didn't work
well on Linux so I ended up having to use Windows to transfer files.

\subsubsection*{Custom Roms}

So in theory the solution to this is rooting and installing a custom rom.
I do prefer this method to using the stock software on the phone, but it has
its downsides.
I have to wipe my phone and manually install the updates and hope it doesn't
brick my phone.
Further, depending on the phone, the developer community may not have all the
available drivers, so I may not be able to get that great of a rom.

\subsubsection*{Android Is Closed}

In theory the iPhone is ``closed'' and Android is open.
But as a comparison, I can get timely updates for my laptop on Linux (which is
open), but I can't get (important) updates on Android in a timely manner because
it is controlled by the hardware manufacturer and the wireless provider.
Further, on Linux I can install any kind of crazy distro I want whereas on
Android I have to stick with stock or with what the developer community was
able to come up with based on availability of drivers.

\subsubsection*{The Trade-off}

So Android is supposed to be great because it is more open, hence more
customizable, and is better on the price to harware quality ratio.
Do these still hold for me?

First, I think that Android is closed too.
As far as customizing my phone, after using Android for almost two years, my
workflow naturally has gravitated towards just using the stock settings and
focusing on a grid of icons.
For this iPhone is actually better because it only has a grid of icons instead
of a more complex two-layered approach of a home screen and app drawer.

Second, with a contract, the newest iPhone is \$200.  Top of the line
Android phones are \$300. The iPhone has great all-around hardware (including
perhaps the best camera on a phone).  The iPhone is actually a pretty good deal
financially for what you get.  Also, it is worth noting that in the used market
iPhones hold their value better than Android phones and are easier to sell.

What else is better about iPhone?

People generally make apps for iPhone before Android.
Virtually any app in the App Store will work on a new iPhone because there are
literally only a few iPhones and they all run the same exact OS.  Often,
if an app is on both iPhone and Android, it is better on iPhone (for example,
every app from the Church). On Android, an app may not be supported on every
device; if an app is only supported on a select number of devices, then you
pretty much can count on never having support for that app.

Mobile Safari is also a more plesant experience than the Android Browser.
Pinch to zoom is better.
Tap to zoom works better.
I like the features it has.
Also, websites tend to do a better job at building mobile versions of their
site for iPhone than for Android.

I also reiterate the support issue.
It is nicer knowing that your phone will work, will get bug fixes, and will run
the latest version of the OS.

I will mention there are things that are better about Android still, but I
in a lot of cases I don't care or I actually prefer the iPhone alternative.

