\subsection*{June 15, 2012}

I had a few thoughts over the past couple days.

I read an article on a blog I read describing a star researcher who has had
success by mastering techniques.  One of the things that has been
limiting in my academic career---although, depending on my future career
choices, this could be a moot point---has been that I don't read mathematical
papers.  I seem to rely on my limited store of knowledge to solve the limited
set of research problems of which I am aware.
In another life, I would change this habit and regularly read papers, learn
techniques, and in general build my store of mathematical knowledge.

Lately I have been spending a lot of time on research.  I have done the
following:
\begin{itemize}
 \item Worked a lot on the so-called Lance-Tapper conjecture.  I proved it in
at least one special case.
\item Worked on a problem my advisor put forth to me.  I have come up with some
results, but there is still more work to be done.
\item Worked on a paper we are putting together on real ideals based on some
work I have done.
\end{itemize}

In the meantime, here are things I haven't done which I should be doing:
\begin{itemize}
 \item Put out more resumes.
 \item Worked on getting a version of my dissertation published.
\end{itemize}

Of my job prospects, given my current enjoyment of mathematics, I have
been more excited about those opportunities which are more mathematical
(specifically the NSA).  I got a call from FICO about a consultant position,
and I was a little bit unexcited about it because it would be a transition
away from the work I have been doing (lately) towards a more social and
statistical realm.  This leads me to wonder if I want a postdoc in the future.
The problem with that is that I couldn't get a postdoc for another year, plus it
is a bump down in salary.

