\subsection*{July 7, 2012}

Let me cover various topics from the past couple weeks.

\subsubsection*{FICO}

I flew out to San Rafael, California, on Tuesday (July 3, 2012) to interview
for a consultant position.  My feeling going into and coming out of the
experience was apprehension.  I still went and did it on the basis of wanting
interview experience.

As for the interview itself, I did not really feel that the position was a good
fit for me.  The position called for a lot of talking to clients about
projects, and it was different from the research background I am used to.
Also, I am not a statistics person, yet this position called for a lot of
statistics.  Finally, the position called for leadership on projects, and I am
just starting out.

Ultimately, however, they called back on Friday to say that I did not get the
job.  The comment I received was that they went with someone with more
optimization experience.
I will say that I am relieved for a couple reasons.  First, I wanted the NSA
job more; I likely would have turned down the position if I did get it.
Second, which is a larger issue, is that I am refocusing my interests on
mathematics itself.

\subsubsection*{Mathematics}

I have spent the last months working on
mathematical research problems.  I have somehow found a renewed joy of
mathematics.  I am digging in deep into writing up some results that I have.  I
am frantically trying to solve a couple more problems (the Lance-Tapper
conjecture principal of those).  In this rush, I started to realize some things.
Especially after submitting my NC harmonics paper for publication (it was
accepted, incidentally),
I realize that I can write papers with results I publish.
I realized that one can site others' results in papers.
I realized that I can read mathematical papers in order to find out more about
topics I am researching and to look for potential techniques I can use. (And I
have read through more papers in the past week than I had the past year or two
combined.)  Basically, I am all of the sudden figuring out how to be a proper
mathematician.

Here is the problem: I figured it all out \textit{after} I finished graduate
school.  I am rounding into a proper mathematician too late.
I have been going forward with my plan to get a job
outside of academia.  I felt a spiritual confirmation of said plan.  I'm down to
one job prospect where being a mathematician and working outside of academia are
feasible, the NSA position.  The logical part of me wonders whether or not I
would be better off with a postdoc.  I chose to have a family, however, and as
such I need a job now instead of next year when I could possibly get a postdoc.

In hindsight, I like my life as it is.
I feel like if I could just be strict about keeping a schedule of when I study
and when I don't think about math, I could have a well-balanced life doing math
and raising a family.

\subsubsection*{Talking to People}

So tonight it came to a point where Allison confronted me about my not being
friendly with people.  Frankly, I gave up on being friendly with people a long
time ago.  In most social situations, I simply don't try to make friends.  I
realized in talking to her the extent of how much this hurts her.  I need to
do better.  Honestly, however, the first major hurdle is wanting to do better.
Sincerely, I like not having to talk to people.  It suits me.

\subsection*{July 14, 2012}

I have an interesting life dilemma.

Over the past while I have been obsessed with doing mathematics.
I solved a problem which my advisor posed to me, and I am feverishly trying to
write it up.
I also might have solved an open conjecture; I need to go through things more
closely to see; in my possible solution, I actually solve a stronger problem
which is a hard Nullstellensatz for NC polynomials.
All of the sudden, my mathematics portfolio is blossoming.  I am finding a
passion for mathematics that I didn't have before.

On the other hand, I am surrounded by people in my life who don't feel the same
way about mathematics as I do and hence are not as understanding of my newly
found obsession for mathematics.  I keep feeling like I just don't have enough
time to do math with all of the demands on my attention from my family.  It
sounds ridiculous to put math over my family, and it is ridiculous.

I now have to (still) find a job.
I rejected academia.  Did I make the wrong choice?
Now that I have found some self-confidence and success with my mathematics, I
am at the end of my academic career, and I won't get to build on it.

\subsection*{July 27, 2012}

\subsubsection*{NSA Interview}

On Sunday July 22 I flew to Maryland for my interview with the NSA.
I stayed in a Courtyard Marriott during the course of my stay.

On the first day I had a polygraph test.  It was horrible.
For some reason, I became uncomfortable during the latter part of the
examination and I started failing the test.  The examiner took a very hostile
turn towards me and accused me of lying to him, of having committed some
serious crimes.  I did not take it well.  They offered to schedule a do-over
for Thursday of this week.  I accepted the do-over, and as such I had to stay
in Maryland for an additional day.

The second day was an interview with the mathematics group at the NSA.
I got to go on the main NSA campus, which was cool.  The mathematicians I
interviewed with were nice (including that the first person I interviewed with
was a member of the church, which put me at ease).  I gave a talk, as planned,
and I felt that it went well, although it's hard to gauge how well my talks
ever go.  It was a more positive experience than before.

The third day was a psychological interview.  It was fine.

The last day was my do-over on the polygraph.  I eventually passed it as I was
able to be more calm and have more conviction in my answers.  Still, I found
the polygraph process to be aggravating.

\subsubsection*{Keith}

My brother Keith is stationed at the NSA.  We have not been close ever since he
became an angry person during our adolescence.  My mom made me email him so that
we could do something during my stay.  He ended up wanting to do stuff every
night until bedtime.  I was grateful for the opportunity to reach out to him.  I
let him talk about a lot of things that he is personally interested in, and I
felt a lot of positive energy from that experience.  I also felt for him because
it seemed like he doesn't have a lot of people he hangs out with because he was
very eager to hang out with me every day.  I am grateful that, if nothing else,
to have been pushed into spending time with him.

\subsubsection*{Pondering My Future}

I don't know what to think about my future career.

The NSA position has a lot of good points to it.
I would be making about as much money as I could reasonably expect to make out
of college (nearly \$90,000 be year, plus great benefits, plus other moneysaving
perks).  I would be forced to spend exactly 40 hours a week on my work, which is
positive for my family and church life.
I would be doing mathematics---other jobs I have looked at haven't had the
title mathematician, and I have become increasingly pessimistic about such jobs.
 These are three great qualities.

What is wrong with that then?  

First, I am being presumptuous to assume that I would even get the job at this
point; I felt good about my interviews, but I don't know if I passed; I don't
know how I compare to the other mathematicians who are applying; I don't know
how hard it is to pass a background check.

Second, I don't have the clear spiritual feeling about it that I had when I
made other life decisions---for example, going to UCSD, getting married, etc.  I
have actually been feeling a little lousy.  This is confusing because I did have
a clear feeling about not becoming a professor; I had a clear feeling about not
becoming a quant; I thought I had a good feeling about becoming an actuary, but
I have given it up after (a) getting a clear feeling to not go to an interview
for an actuarial internship and (b) seeing how hard it was to get looked at for
entry-level actuarial positions as an over-qualified Ph.D.  Also, I feel good
about mathematics now.  I have had some good successes these past few months.  I
don't necessarily think that that implies that I ought to pursue academia.  I
do, however, want to follow the spirit and figure out what is right for our
family.

Finally, the big tradeoff is that I have to become super-secretive about my
professional life.  I can't bring gadgets to work or (probably) email home
during the day.  I won't have the flexibility to work from home.  I have to go
through the government to travel outside of the country or make foreign friends.
 It feels like I am selling out my freedom. 

As of now, I am really confused as to what I should do.  I want to take care of
my family, and the paycheck would make things much easier for me on that front,
yet ultimately I need to do what the spirit dictates.

\subsection*{June 28, 2012}

Today was Saturday.
I have had a lousy feeling about the NSA position, hence I have been thinking
more and more about going for a position in academia (starting with a postdoc
likely).  As such, I then became franctically fixated on coming up with a
mathematical result.  Today I wanted to prove a powerful non-commutative
nullstellensatz, and I ended up working most of the day on that.
I think this was bad for me, and I think that I need to stop working at home so
much.

