\subsection*{August 6, 2012}

I am trying to be better.

\subsection*{August 10, 2012}

Today I got the news that I passed the preliminary meeting of the
NSA mathematics hiring committee.  If I am approved on my security check and by
the second committee, I will get a job offer.
This has got me thinking about my future.

First of all, I can't really justify a way I don't take the job if offered it
given my family's needs.  Allison especially has been putting a lot of pressure
on me to be applying for more jobs (I haven't in a long time).  Given that the
NSA position pays so well (almost \$90 K per year), it would solve all of my
financial problems.

Next, I have been complusively trying to get my research done.
I have lots of material that I am just trying to get typed up so that I can
ship it out.  Most of it will futurely be published in journals I hope.  I
have, to date, had two of my papers now accepted for publication, and another
one has now been submitted.  I have enjoyed being able to get so many
mathematical results.

Therefore, what about that career in academia?
I think I could do it.
However, where would the money come from?
Also, I have had a hard time meeting the demands of my work and meeting the
demands of my family.  It has really been tearing me apart.

\subsection*{August 12, 2012}

I will reflect on my life in this post.

\subsubsection*{I Am Inherently Lazy}

I have thought about and felt guilty about various aspects of this during this
past week.  In a lot of what I do, I take the path of least resistance.  I
specifically feel guilty about shirking my church responsibilities and about not
being a good roommate/person to live with because I don't do housework.

How have I gotten by while being so lazy?  I have a few ideas.

First, I was
blessed in this life to have a talent for schoolwork.  I have no concept of how
hard people have to work in school.  Today I was thinking about a couple of
past experiences.

One was a psychology class I took my first year of college.
I took it seriously, so I new I needed to read the assigned textbook chapters.
As far as I can remember, all I did to study for the test was read the chapters
once through, and then review them shortly before the exams.  As we had exams,
I aced them.  By contrast, many people in the class for some reason felt that
the exams were difficult (including an old friend from high school who was an
honors student.) A related experience to this was getting the highest grades in
the class in my history of opera class because I had the best memory in the
class.

A final example to share is my first year of graduate school.  My
method of study for the most part was to do my homework, do some review before
the exams, and nothing else.  My topology teacher decided we needed to do some
work together, so he had us present our solutions to problems.  On many
occasions I was the only one to come up with solutions to specific problems,
and I always solved every problem.  Before that, I had no idea I was doing so
much better at the homework than everyone else. (If I remember correctly, I
wasn't actually scoring that well due to tough grading and due to my writing up
of the answers.)  I also recall comments from people in my program about how
difficult the first year was, even though I didn't feel like it was that
difficult.

My point is, I have been allowed to complete school---that is, the most
important vocational activity in my life---with relative ease.  As a byproduct,
I haven't been forced to struggle to succeed at much in life, hence I can be
lazy.

My second point, however, is that sometimes I am not lazy.  If I get excited
about something, I put in work to do well at it.  For example, in my math
research, I have had breakthroughs after intensely working on problems.
In my first-year graduate-school courses, I mentioned that I did my homework
and not much else; what I should note is that my homework was intense and that
I put in the focused effort to do it because I was excited about it. (It was so
hard, as I mentioned, most people did not complete all of it.)  Letting my
excitement spur on an intense focus in me has been a successful strategy for
succeeding at school.  On the other hand, I can name things I am not excited
about: cleaning the apartment, talking to people in my callings at church,
waking up early, etc.  It also might come back to haunt me with my job search
(I am basically banking on getting a position with the NSA at this point.)

How can I overcome laziness?

