\subsubsection*{My Mathematics Education}

I have had occasion to think about my past mathematics education.
Jonan is taking Algebra 1 as a $7^{\mbox{\tiny th}}$ grader,
and I have had to help him complete his homework each day.
He has had a lot of trouble doing his work correctly.

In contrast, when I was in $7^{\mbox{\tiny th}}$ grade, I had to take
Pre-Algebra.  In $6^{\mbox{\tiny th}}$ grade, my teacher had us work
independently through our mathematics curriculum.  I got through a sizable
chunk of the book by myself over the first part of the year.  Then for some
reason I never did much with mathematics for the rest of the year (see below
for a guess). We were given placement test for mathematics at the end of the
year and I placed into Pre-Algebra.  I remember not having been exposed to
algebra, and hence getting a lot of the algebra questions wrong.

In $7^{\mbox{\tiny th}}$ grade, I had my worst year academically.  I was also
going through my parents' divorce in $6^{\mbox{\tiny th}}$ and $7^{\mbox{\tiny
th}}$ grade, so I had a hard time.  My last semester I pulled horrible grades.
However, during this time, we started covering some simple algebra in my math
class.  I was in a ``gifted'' program, so everyone in my class was advanced,
however I started noticing that where others were having a hard time getting
some of the material, I found it to be easy.  I remember being able to do
algebra problems very quickly in my head while others had to sit down and work
it out.  I latched onto mathematics at that point.  I started doing extra
credit mathematics assignments---it was the only thing I liked to do.  My
$7^{\mbox{\tiny th}}$ grade year I must have pulled all C's and D's except for
an A in Pre-Algebra and a B-something in gym.

In $8^{\mbox{\tiny th}}$ grade we moved to Utah and my mom managed to get me
placed into Geometry, in effect skipping Algebra 1.  I dominated that class as
well, which boosted my self-confidence.  I remember, however, my teacher doing
a few things which irk me as I look back on them.  One was separating me from
working with the brighter students in the class, instead urging me to help the
slower students in the class; I believe this was
harmful to my development and has contributed to my difficulties in talking
about mathematics with fellow students in graduate school.
There are other things that annoyed me as well.

In $9^{\mbox{\tiny th}}$ grade I had a good mathematics teacher.
I also placed in the top 50 for $9^{\mbox{\tiny th}}$ graders in the Utah State
Mathematics Competition.  I don't remember ``dominating'' the class, although I
felt I did well.

In $10^{\mbox{\tiny th}}$ grade, I really started to dominate my classes again.
I remember scoring perfect scores on virtually every exam.
I also remember that I finished reading our textbook halfway through the year
and started studying calculus independently.
I also remember an episode where my misguided guidance counselor told me
calculus would be too hard for me and that I ought not take calculus.

In $11^{\mbox{\tiny th}}$ grade, I really dominated my calculus class.  We
would take lots of days where we would not learn new material but would work on
our homework.  I would have nothing to do in these days but study other
subjects because I could finish my homework quickly the first day I got it.
I passed the Calculus AB test with a 5, which is the top grade.

My $12^{\mbox{\tiny th}}$ grade class was a missed opportunity for me because I
took ``independent study'' Calculus BC and Statistics.  In hindsight, I would
have been better served by taking college mathematics that year.  I passed the
Calculus BC test with a 5 (easily) as well as the AP Statistics test.  I had
gotten to the point where I realized I new more than my teachers about
mathematics.

