\subsection*{December 12, 2012}

I gave my students their final exam.  The exam was more conceptual than
the midterms.  In the class, the first midterm was way too easy and most
of the class aced it.  The second midterm was at a proper difficulty
level and scores fell along a proper curve.

Students were frustrated that the difficulty of the exams varied so
dramatically.  I agree that this wasn't good and I have gained an appreciation
for how hard it is to write an exam.

It seems that plenty of students struggled mightily with the conceptual
material.  I have started to realize why it is important to test the
students on this.  On the students' homework the ``harder'' problems are the
ones where the students have to think about how to setup a problem.
Arguably developing the skill of setting up a problem is as important as
learning the specific material, if not more so.
I wonder how many students navigated the course by relying on others to help
them set up a problem for them; if there were any such students taking the
final, they must have struggled on this exam.

On this vein, I also started to see that a lot of students came into my class
expecting it to be like high school math.  In high school, you go to class
every day, the teacher tells you how to do a type of problem, and then you do
20 of those.  My stereotype of it is that it is all straightforward.  Students
comments showed they did not like that they couldn't just pick everything up
from the lecture.  

As someone who just gets how to set things up, who just gets conceptual
material, I didn't have an appreciation for the difference in difficulty
between calculus and what came before it.

I also understand the other side.  Students also need a rock solid foundation
of basic technical skills.  They can learn concepts as they go through their
career.  There should be a balance though.  I want students to think.

\subsection*{December 16, 2012}

I was able to finish up my class work so that we could head out to Utah on
Saturday.  We went to church in St. George, and then we drove to Springville.

I had my students comment about what they liked and didn't like about the
class.  It was interesting to read the responses because there are always those
people who say crazy things.

\includegraphics[scale=0.1]{photo_5.jpeg}

This one was interesting because the student seemed to blame me for not making
her go to class.  You should always go to class if you want a good grade.  This
student ended up with a C-.

\includegraphics[scale=0.1]{photo_4.jpeg}

This one was interesting for a few reasons.
First, the student attacks the test itself as being bad; that accomplishes
nothing; ironically, I thought the test was wonderful because it fit in a ton
of material yet was short enough for everyone to have it be graded quickly and
avoid a mad rush at the end of the exam period.
Second, in class I explained to my
students about the multi-part format; if the student (a) attended lecture,
which I doubt, and (b) payed attention, he could have known this; once again,
even though I put my lecture notes online, it turned out that you need to go to
class. Third, the student claims he had an A going into the final; out of
curiosity I checked back and saw that he didn't have an A going into the final;
he had an 87\% which is over the cusp of a B; this, however, included a below
average score on the easy midterm; that midterm score was technically an A, but
everything else about his performance suggested B- or C+.  The poor final
pushed him down to a C, however.

\includegraphics[scale=0.1]{photo_3.jpeg}

This one was interesting because I set out a final review and specifically
included things in it which would be in some way on the final.  The so-called
old midterms and other classes' tests were actually dissimilar to the actual
final. I wonder if the student would have done better on the final had he
completed the practice problems I set out.

